Anonymous Fri 10 Jul 2020 00:56:42 No.31402416 Report
Quoted By: >>31402444 >>31402600 >>31403289
>>31401838
>art is harder than writing
lol

It's easier to judge art because you see more of it. Unless you are a really voracious reader you won't get through much and you'll dump a lot of mediocre writing early or halfway through. An artist that can knock out a great drawing a day has seven drawings a week for you to judge them by. A writer that can knock out a solid 1000 words a day, has 7000 words that will become part of a story. It can take a writer several weeks or months to produce one good work. So you can judge an artists monthly output in a few minutes, whereas it would take you a couple hours to read a prolific writers output and it would likely only be part of a larger work.

Practicing is cumulative for artists as well. Their daily work can be critiqued and their technique can improve quickly. The huge time commitment for writing a story of merit means that it takes longer to get good at it. Art has more technical critiquing available to it as well, it is much harder to get feedback as a writer because of the asymmetric time commitment for the consumer of the work.

In the digital age it's actually pretty easy to get good at making art, you don't need to waste materials. A computer and time will have you making really good stuff from practice alone. Whereas the core skills of writing (phrasing, story, characterization) haven't had tools developed to make them easier. In fact the general advance of culture has made telling compelling narratives even harder because media saturation has risen everyone's expectations so high.

Look at any niche or fetish, does it have more great art or more great writing?
If you measure in hours of labor I can't think of anything that has anywhere near as much good writing as good art.
Logically speaking, wouldn't there be less of whichever is harder to make?

There are other factors too, it's easier to monetize art. So more people are being encouraged and supported to make more of it. But in general my point stands.

Going to throw my 2 cents in. People are more forgiving of bad art than of bad writing. People will be more forgiving on shitty or mediocre artists as long as the drawing(s) are of their fetish and/or waifu/husbando. Or you still like some bad drawings because they contain aspects you like or even they're bad in an enjoyable way or some sort. Or people just can't tell the drawing is bad until someone points how fucky some anatomy looks or other weird parts. But with bad or even slight bad writing it can kill people's interest much much faster. Even how you format your writing can make people instantly quit like wall of text stories with no paragraph breaks or such. A story with bad grammar can instantly kill desire to continue reading it since you have to read the text and have your brain try to fix the grammar at the same time if it's bad enough. Or writers not following the rule of starting a new paragraph each time a different person has dialogue making scenes of who's talking confusing.
tl;dr, reading requires more concentration than looking at pictures
